          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Stern warning and call for action</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-jan-9-2.jpg" alt="Stern warning and call for action" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">​​Turkey has issued a stern warning to Kurdish forces in Syria, threatening military action unless its demands are met for a peaceful transition. Foreign Minister Hakan Fidan emphasized that Ankara would intervene militarily if the Kurdish-led People's Protection Units (<a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-09-01-2025-h2-4-ykg" target="_blank">YKG</a>)  failed to comply. Turkey considers them a terrorist group linked to the Kurdistan Workers' Party (<a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-09-01-2025-h2-5-pkk" target="_blank">PKK</a>) in Turkey. Fidan gave Turkey's conditions, including the withdrawal of foreign fighters linked to the People’s Protection Units from Syria.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">With a history of cross-border operations against Kurdish forces, Ankara appears poised for further action as it seeks to safeguard its interests in post-Assad Syria. Fidan noted <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-09-01-2025-h2-6-turkey-expectations" target="_blank">Turkey's expectation</a> that Syria's new interim leadership would address the YPG issue and said it’s ready to give time for Damascus and the Kurdish group discussion. </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-divider border-width="1px" border-style="solid" border-color="lightgrey" padding="10px 12px" />
