          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500;">Far-right dominance continues</h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Herbert Kickl's potential rise as Austria's far-right leader shows an emerging pattern in European politics that challenges European unity. The Austrian Freedom Party, led by Kickl, became the strongest party in Austria’s parliament for the first time since World War II. The party shows strong <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-09-01-2025-h3-6-alignment-with-viktor-orban" target="_blank">alignment with Viktor Orban</a>, who supports forging closer ties with Russia, blocking aid to Ukraine, and opposing migration. Kickl also shares his party’s EU-sceptic stance, and their election manifesto called for restricting EU powers and developing an “Austrian Fortress” within the Schengen area.</p>
          <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">However, Austria has more companions on the same page, particularly in Central Europe. In addition to Hungary’s Orban, their Slovak neighbors, led by <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-09-01-2025-h3-7-robert-fico" target="_blank">Robert Fico</a>, are on the same page geopolitically. He recently threatened to reduce aid to Ukraine refugees over the Russian gas debacle and pledged to block Ukraine’s inclusion in NATO. The <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-09-01-2025-h3-8-2025-czech-elections" target="_blank">2025 Czech elections</a> might give them another Central European companion, as the populist right-wing party is soaring in the polls. 
</p>
        </mj-text>
