          <h2 style="font-size:20px;line-height:1.2;font-weight:500; margin-top:2px !important">What is the situation with Tibet?</h2>
        </mj-text>
         <mj-image padding="10px 12px" width="600px" src="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com/email/images/gp-jan-9-3.png" alt="Why did Argentina decline BRICS membership?" href="https://www.geopoliticalsummary.com" />
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">Tibet is an autonomous region in China, located in the western part of the country, and is recognized by the Chinese government as a crucial part of China. Historically, Tibet was an independent kingdom and became a theocratic state led by the Dalai Lama until 1950, when China's People's Liberation Army entered the region. In 1951, the Chinese government and Tibetan representatives signed the <a href="https://link.altdaily.co/gs-09-01-2025-f1-11-seventeen-point-agreement" target="_blank">Seventeen Point Agreement</a>, establishing Chinese control over Tibet while allowing it some autonomy. Many Tibetans and advocates for Tibetan independence claim that this agreement was made under pressure and not what the Tibetans wanted. 
</p>
           <p style="font-size:16px;line-height:1.4;">There are several debates surrounding Tibet's autonomy, which remains a sensitive topic. A standard narrative is that the <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-09-01-2025-f2-12-chinese-government-oppresses-Tibetans" target="_blank">Chinese government oppresses Tibetans</a>. The narrative held by China is that Tibet was an oppressive feudal and <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-09-01-2025-f3-13-religious-society" target="_blank">religious society</a>, and Chinese control improved the livelihood. Some say that a lot of the “Free Tibet movement” is prompted by the CIA and the West to smear China. The CIA did fund and support the <a href="https://link.geopoliticalsummary.com/gs-09-01-20205-f4-14-tibetian-resistance-movement" target="_blank">Tibetan resistance movement</a> during the 1950s and 1960s, primarily to counter Chinese influence in the region, and was put to a stop in the early 1970s when the US foreign policy became more open to China. 
</p>
        </mj-text>
